b) Since the generating function for a Poisson distribution is Pf = e^(-lambda+lambda_s), the convolution of Pf* * Pf = e^(-lambda+lambda_2) * e^(-lambda+lambda_s) = e^(2*(-lambda+lambda_s)) which is still the generating function of a Poisson distribution with a factor of two in the exponent of the function.

2)a) & b)Here we have plots of a Rayleigh distribution repeatedly averaged. It starts to look Gaussian quickly, but plotting against a log scale shows it has a long way to go to be truly Gaussian after 13 averages. We then attempt averaging 113 and 613 times, and we see that we pass the normal distribution somewhere between 113 and 613 averages. Our 613 averaged distribution appears to be Gaussian with a sigma of less than 1.

Version 1:
Our background distribution for our pixel is just a Gaussian distribution with width X = 4. We're looking for a signal of strength Y = 9. What we need to do is calculate the probability our background will generate a signal of strength 9 or greater- so we will integrate our distribution from 9 upwards to get our probability, then we will invert our function to find our sigma value.
x = linspace(-20,20,101)
x =
-20.0000 -19.6000 -19.2000 -18.8000 -18.4000 -18.0000 -17.6000 -17.2000 -16.8000 -16.4000 -16.0000 -15.6000 -15.2000 -14.8000 -14.4000 -14.0000 -13.6000 -13.2000 -12.8000 -12.4000 -12.0000 -11.6000 -11.2000 -10.8000 -10.4000 -10.0000 -9.6000 -9.2000 -8.8000 -8.4000
Gaus1 = makedist('Normal',0,4)
Gaus1 =
NormalDistribution Normal distribution mu = 0 sigma = 4
Gaus = normpdf(x,0,4)
Gaus =
0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0000 0.0001 0.0001 0.0002 0.0002 0.0003 0.0004 0.0006 0.0008 0.0011 0.0015 0.0020 0.0026 0.0034 0.0044 0.0056 0.0071 0.0089 0.0110
normcdf(12,0,4,'upper')
ans = 0.0013
prob = .4*sum(Gaus(1,81:101))
prob = 0.0016
sigma = norminv(0.0013)
sigma = -3.0115
disp(prob)
0.0016
disp(sigma)
-3.0115
So we cannot claim a discovery, since sigma is equal to 3.0115.
For this section we need to take into account the fact we are looking at 10k pixels. Since we are going to be comparing this new distribution to just one pixel, we cannot only convolve the original distribution 10k times - we will need to average it. I attempted to do this and crashed my MATLAB, below is the code I would use to calculate the probability and sigma if I were able to. I could not directly calculate these, but since our distribution will be wider our sigma should be lower than in Version 1. This means our sigma will be less than 5 and we cannot claim a discovery.

4) a)
%We defined the width of our distribution to be 4, so integrating upwards
%from 5 sigma should give us a probability with an inverse of 5 sigma.
%Below we confirm this
Prob5 = normcdf(20,0,4,'upper')
Prob5 = 2.8665e-07
Sigma5 = norminv(2.86e-7)
Sigma5 = -5.0004
disp(Prob5)
2.8665e-07
disp(Sigma5)
-5.0004
b) Our averaged distribution should have a sigma that is shrunk by 10k, proportional to our number of trials, so we should have a signal of our sigma5 signal from part a divided by 10k, or a signal of .002.
c)The penalty decreases as the trials increase because the effect of dividing our signal has diminishing returns.
d) Our sensitivity threshold would change proportionally by orders of magnitude.
